args: Meene is always going out lately\nand she never tells me where.
She's never really been into secrets\nand stuff before, you know?
If it weighs on your mind, why not ask her?
Yeah, but what if it's...you know? Delicate.\nLike a boyfriend or something.
Look, there's no dang problem! It's just\na mother-daughter sort of thing, okay?!\nIt's weird to talk about this stuff with her!
Then I suppose you will need to find out\nsome other way.
Ugh. The more I talk about this,\nthe more it's starting to bug me.
Yeah, but that one's okay. Now hush up\nso I can make with the peeping.
To you and humans, maybe, but Meene's\na faerie. Now please! Hush already!
A seat has been readied for you;\nyour father said as much.
A lovely, yet hollow gesture. I'm sure there\nisn't a single task of import he would\nentrust to his failed youngest.
While it is fact that your brothers and\nsisters are talented, I see no cause to\ndenigrate yourself so.
You're right. Here I fancy myself as a\nchanged faerie, but I slip right back into\nold habits. It's simply terrible.
I wonder if I'll stop being myself\nif I return?
No. Not going back was never\nan option for me.
Soon, I'll have no choice but to return\nto the Faerie Kingdom.
Will Meene really return to the\nFaerie Kingdom?
I never heard it from her in as many words,\nbut I learned enough to see the writing on\nthe wall some time ago.
Apparently faeries of a certain age\ngrow in size for a time.
They use those years to learn about the\noutside world, then head back home once\nthey're ready to shrink down again.
Once they do, that's that—they never\nset foot outside their kingdom again.
Yeah. We won't ever see her again.
If I'm honest, it doesn't feel real.\nShe's been there since... Well, forever.
I can't really imagine what it'd be like if\nshe just...wasn't, you know?
I knew the day would come, but I tried not\nto think about it and kept putting it off...
Now I finally have to face it—but at least\nI already know what I need to do.
I've got to grow up—and fast.\nEnough to be all right on my own.
I can't have Meene worrying about me\nafter she leaves.
Ilia still isn't back. Do you think something\nmight have happened to her?
Why in the world would she travel to the\ncapital now, of all times? Why didn't you\nstop her, Mordecai?
It was in her own best interest—\nand in yours, Meene.
What is THAT supposed to mean?
And where have you been, young lady?!
Just to the capital and back.
Negotiating sales of a new invention!\nI'm working on developing some new\ndistribution routes.
But why NOW? You know the army is\nbusy looking for you.
Was it something you really had to do in\nthe middle of all this danger? Because it\nsure doesn't sound like it.
No. It had to be now.
Why? What could possibly be more\nimportant than your LIFE?
I'm not saying that! I'm just...
No buts, young lady. You have to learn\nto take proper care of yours—
I'M FINE, OKAY?! You can stop worrying\nabout me all the freaking time!
I'm not a little girl anymore!
Sorry, I'm... Look, I'm going to bed.
*sigh* It's never easy. Sorry about that.
That's all right. But are YOU well?
Truthfully, I'm a bit shocked.\nWe've never really fought before.
She's right, though: She's a wonderful,\nmature woman now, and I need to learn\nto let go of my baby girl.
I'm going to step out for some air.\nYou two go ahead and sleep.
They love each other so much, yet they\nstill manage to hurt one another...\nLove is a tricky thing indeed.
There are as many forms of love as there\nare people, so what do you suppose Meene\nwill choose in the end?
I don't know. But whatever it is, I hope it's\na choice neither she nor Ilia will regret.
